Chapter 2: A Recipe for Suspicion

The silence in Leo's apartment was a physical thing, a dough over-proofing in the heat of his own panic. It pressed against his eardrums, a low-frequency hum beneath the sporadic patter of rain on the single west-facing window. The droplets slid down the glass like tears, each one a tiny, translucent bead that seemed to hold the promise of a thousand midnights. It had been thirty-six hours since Julian Thorne's death. The police had come and gone from his own doorstep, their questions polite but their eyes like scalpels, dissecting his answers. The echo of their shoes on the hallway's terrazzo floor still seemed to linger, a ghostly reminder of the intrusion that had shattered his carefully constructed world.

Leo's eyes wandered to the kitchen, where the remnants of his failed attempt to cook something normal still lingered. The air was heavy with the acrid scent of burnt vinegar, a bitter reminder of his own ineptitude. He'd spent the interim not sleeping, but moving in a tight, compulsive orbit between his narrow galley kitchen and the fortress of books that lined his living room, his socks whispering over floorboards worn smooth by a century of other anxious tenants. The soft creak of the wooden floorboards beneath his feet was a familiar comfort, a reminder that even in the midst of chaos, there was still a sense of order to be found.

As he stood there, the silence began to take on a life of its own. It was a palpable thing, a living entity that seemed to pulse with a rhythm all its own. The rain drummed on, a relentless beat that echoed the pounding of his heart. He felt like he was drowning in it, suffocating under the weight of his own emotions. The police had asked him so many questions, their words a blur of concern and curiosity. But it was the look in their eyes that had really unsettled him – a look that said they were searching for something, anything, to explain the brutal, senseless murder of a man he'd known for only a few weeks.

Leo's gaze drifted back to the bookshelf, where his collection of cookbooks seemed to loom like sentinels. The leather-bound volumes were a testament to his love of history, a love that had been forged in the fires of his own failures. He'd spent years researching, experimenting, and perfecting his craft, all in the hopes of creating something truly special. And yet, despite his best efforts, he'd always felt like an outsider, a stranger in a world that seemed to value technique over passion.

He ran a finger along the spines of the books, feeling the raised letters and embossed designs. The tactile sensation was soothing, a reminder that even in the midst of chaos, there was still beauty to be found. His hand stopped on a volume the color of dried blood: The Forme of Cury, a modern facsimile. Not old enough. The thought was a rasp in his mind, a nagging sense of doubt that he couldn't shake.

He needed the source, the root, the thing itself. He needed to see the stain of the original. The thought sent a shiver down his spine, a cold, creeping sensation that seemed to seep into his bones. He needed to understand the secrets that lay hidden within the pages of this ancient book, secrets that could hold the key to unlocking the mystery of Julian Thorne's death.

Leo found the Libellus de Arte Coquinaria on a high shelf, requiring a wooden step-stool that groaned under his weight. The sound was like a ship's timber straining, a reminder of the weight of history that lay before him. The book was heavy, a slab of history, its cover embossed with the image of a porpoise. He'd paid three months' rent for it years ago, a trophy from his critic days, a thing he'd bought to prove he understood grandeur, not just technique.

He carried it to his broad, scarred oak worktable, the only clear surface in the room, its wood stained with rings of wine, oil, and regret. A fine cloud of dust, golden in the thin afternoon light, puffed from its edges. The brass clasp was cool, a reassuring weight in his hand. He lifted it, and the book exhaled a dusty, papery sigh. His fingers, usually steady, trembled slightly as he eased the cover open.

A dry, protesting creak echoed in the quiet room, a sound that seemed to reverberate through every cell in his body. The pages weren't just seen; they pressed against his eyes. The Latin text wasn't merely black, but a furious, spiked wall, each letter dug into the vellum with a vengeful hand. He blinked, his own breath catching in his throat.

Then, the beasts. A dragon, coiled within the curve of a 'D', glared with a tiny eye of emerald green. His index finger hovered above it, not daring to touch. In the margins, a painted monkey leered, a half-peeled fig in its claw, and a jester's crimson tongue seemed to waggle as the page settled. But his gaze skipped, searched, and finally locked.

There. A peacock, its fan a hundred shimmering eyes, lay resurrected in full plumage on a platter. A swan, sculpted from sugar, arched its neck over a parsley sea. His lips parted, a silent, hungry shape. He traced the air above a marzipan Jerusalem, the gold leaf on its towers drinking the pale window-light and glowing with a faint, warm thrum he could almost feel on his skin. The room faded. There was only the slow, deep pull of his inhalation, the book's jeweled colors painting his still face.

He flipped past "Blankmanger" and "Connynges in Bruet," the pages whispering like old leaves, his eyes scanning for the dish that had ended Julian Thorne. Crane roasted with a galentyne sauce… No. Hare in talbotace… No. His finger, smudged with ancient dust and the salt of his own skin, traced down a page. The parchment texture was rough, simulating vellum. There.

Porpus in Savce Sawge.

Porpoise in Savory Sauce. The very dish he'd served to Elara Voss just two weeks ago. His breath hitched, a sharp, papery sound in the quiet room. He hadn't made the connection immediately. Thorne's death was a shockwave, a slamming of the door on a world he'd thought he knew. The memory of that dinner, the laughter, the wine, and the conversation, all seemed to mock him now. He'd been so caught up in the thrill of the evening, the rush of adrenaline as he presented his dish to the esteemed guests, that he'd never stopped to consider the possibility that it might be the key to unraveling the mystery.

Leo's eyes narrowed, his mind racing with the implications. He'd served the porpoise in savory sauce to Elara Voss, a woman he'd met through a mutual acquaintance, a woman with a reputation for being ruthless in her pursuit of perfection. She'd taken one bite, and her eyes had lit up with a fierce, almost feral, enthusiasm. The praise had been effusive, but Leo had sensed a hidden undertone, a warning that he couldn't quite decipher.

He thought back to their conversation, the way she'd asked him about his inspiration, her eyes sparkling with curiosity. He'd told her about the book, about the porpoise, and the way it had seemed to come alive on the plate. She'd listened intently, her expression unreadable, but Leo had sensed a flicker of interest, a spark of recognition that he couldn't quite explain.

And now, it seemed, that spark had ignited a fire that threatened to consume him. He felt a shiver run down his spine as he realized that he might have been more involved in Thorne's death than he'd initially thought. The thought sent a wave of panic crashing through him, a sense of disorientation that left him breathless.

Leo's gaze dropped to the book, his eyes scanning the pages with a newfound sense of urgency. He needed to understand the secrets that lay hidden within its yellowed pages, secrets that could hold the key to unlocking the mystery of Julian Thorne's death. He needed to know if the porpoise in savory sauce was more than just a coincidence, if it was a clue that could lead him to the truth.

As he delved deeper into the book, the words began to blur together, a mad jumble of Latin and recipes that seemed to mock him with their complexity. But Leo refused to give up, his mind racing with the possibilities. He was driven by a fierce determination, a need to uncover the truth, no matter how painful it might be.

The rain continued to fall outside, a relentless beat that echoed the pounding of his heart. But Leo didn't notice, lost as he was in the world of the book, a world of ancient recipes and mysterious ingredients. He was a detective, a seeker of truth, and he would stop at nothing to uncover the secrets that lay hidden within the pages of The Forme of Cury.

As the hours passed, the room grew darker, the shadows deepening into a mysterious, velvety black. But Leo didn't notice, his eyes fixed intently on the book, his mind racing with the implications. He was a man on a mission, driven by a fierce determination to uncover the truth, no matter how painful it might be.

And as the night wore on, the silence in the room grew thicker, a heavy, oppressive blanket that seemed to suffocate him. But Leo didn't feel it, lost as he was in the world of the book, a world of ancient recipes and mysterious ingredients. He was a man on a quest, driven by a fierce determination to uncover the secrets that lay hidden within the pages of The Forme of Cury.

